'''Cannabis in Bosnia and Herzegovina''' is illegal.

==Polling==
In 2016, a survey conducted at the Faculty of Philosophy within [[Mostar University]] found that 92% of students supported legalizing cannabis for medical purposes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bosnia Today |url=http://www.bosniatoday.ba/92-percent-of-students-support-marijuana-legalization-in-bosnia-and-herzegovina/ |title=92 percent of students support marijuana legalization in Bosnia and Herzegovina - Bosnia Today |publisher=Bosniatoday.ba |date= |accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref>

==Possible legalization of medical cannabis==
In 2016 it was announced that the Ministry of Civil Affairs had formed a task force to explore the legalizing of cannabis and cannabinoids for medical purposes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bosnia Today |url=http://www.bosniatoday.ba/bosnia-to-legalize-medical-marijuana-this-year/ |title=Bosnia to legalize medical marijuana this year - Bosnia Today |publisher=Bosniatoday.ba |date= |accessdate=2016-11-30}}</ref>

==Cultivation==
Following the 1992–1995 [[Bosnian War]], Bosnia became a major producer of cannabis, with much of its output being routed through Slovenia and Croatia due to higher prices there.<ref>{{cite book|title=Smuggling in Southeast Europe: The Yugoslav Wars and the Development of Regional Criminal Networks in the Balkans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=srjE2eFi_nsC&pg=PA43|year=2002|publisher=CSD|isbn=978-954-477-099-0|pages=43–}}</ref>

