'''Ianthe Blyden''' (April 14, 1899 – June 30, 1984) was a [[Virgin Islander]], born at a time when the islands were held by the Danish. She trained as a nurse and served for fifty-three years at [[Knud Hansen Memorial Hospital]], for thirty-seven of those years she was head nurse. She was instrumental in the development of nursing in the US Virgin Islands and the influence for establishing the island's nursing board.

==Early life==
Ianthe Amelia Blyden was born on April 14, 1899{{sfn|Funeral Book|2016|p=4}} in the [[Danish West Indies]]. She was the eldest of nine children born to Terecita Blyden, a nurse-midwife, who had come from [[Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Saint John]]. Terecita had been trained by an aunt who had studied the profession in [[Copenhagen]]. The family owned a sugar manufactory in Saint John at [[Annaberg, Saint John, U.S. Virgin Islands|Annaberg]] and another at Mary's Point. Blyden completed her schooling through age thirteen, the maximum schooling at the time.{{sfn|Petrillo|1973|p=30552}}

==Career==
Blyden began her career as a teacher on Saint John at the age of fifteen for a salary of $2.50 per month. After a year, she decided not to pursue teaching and instead went to the Danish Municipal Hospital in [[Charlotte Amalie, U.S. Virgin Islands|Charlotte Amalie]] to study nursing under the doctors there. In 1916, she began working as a nurse for the monthly salary of $5.00. The following year, the Danish West Indies were sold to the United States, which brought in [[United States Navy Nurse Corps|Navy Nurses]] to implement a three-year training program. She became a nurse-anesthetist and worked in the pharmacy and laboratory as an assistant. She also acted as a midwife when needed.{{sfn|Petrillo|1973|p=30552}}

In 1932, during the [[Malaria|malaria epidemic]], she was appointed head nurse, becoming the first native-born islander to hold the post. Climbing the professional ladder, she was made chief nurse, nursing supervisor and finally director of nurses.{{sfn|Petrillo|1973|p=30552}} In 1946, having graduated from the Municipal Hospital School of Nursing, Blyden took a leave from her supervisory duties to complete post-graduate studies in surgical nursing at the [[Lincoln School for Nurses]] in [[The Bronx]], New York City.{{sfn|''The American Journal of Nursing''|1946|p=263}} In the early 1950s, soon after the Danish doctor, Knud Hansen died, the old Danish Hospital was replaced with a new facility, named in his honor.{{sfn|Dyssel|1976|p=11}} In 1952, when the [[Legislature of the Virgin Islands|Colonial Council]] passed the inaugural Nurse Practice Act, Governor [[Morris de Castro]] appointed Blyden, Ilva Benjamin, Clarissa Milligan, Ingerborg Nesbitt, and Josephine Singleton for the Board of Nursing.{{sfn|Christian-Garcia|2001|p=i–ii}} Blyden was the driving force in the formation of the St. Thomas Chapter of the Licensed Practical Nurses Association, which formed in 1956.{{sfn|Legislature of the US Virgin Islands|1976|p=291}}

Blyden retired in 1969 after having served for fifty-three years in nursing with thirty-seven of those as a head nurse.{{sfn|Petrillo|1973|p=30552}}

==Death and legacy==
Blyden died on June 30, 1984 in St. Thomas and her services were held at the Memorial Moravian Church.{{sfn|Funeral Book|2016|p=4}}

